article.description:
Jalen Rose scored 20 points and the 
Chicago Bulls allowed just 12 points in the fourth quarter as
they snapped a 16-game losing streak to the Toronto Raptors with
a 96-83 victory.
article.headline: Bulls winthree straight for second time since 2000
article.linkText: Bulls continue winning ways against Raptors
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- It wasn't so long ago -- just 2½ weeks, in fact -- that the Chicago Bulls were slogging through a nine-game losing streak and wondering when they'd win again. Well, well, well, look at them now. With a 96-83 victory over Toronto on Wednesday, the Bulls have won five of their last six and have a three-game winning streak for only the second time since January 2000. "We just got tired of losing," Eddie Robinson said. "You can only take so much losing. We wanted to put together some kind of a winning streak, and turn our season around." It's not just that the Bulls are finally winning, it's the way they're doing it. Jalen Rose continues to lead Chicago in scoring -- he had 20 against Toronto -- but he's getting help. Donyell Marshall had 17 points and 11 rebounds while Marcus Fizer added 15 points and 13 boards, their second-straight night of double-doubles. Jay Williams had 14 points and seven assists, and Tyson Chandler scored 10. "We're gelling," Jay Williams said. "You're talking about bringing together guys who've never played with each other. We're learning our way. We're learning what to do and what not to do. We're growing together as a team." Morris Peterson scored 22 for the Raptors, and Jerome Williams and Jelani McCoy each finished with 16 points and 11 rebounds. But it wasn't enough for the short-handed Raptors, who were without Vince Carter and Antonio Davis and playing a night after needing overtime to beat Milwaukee. The Raptors shot less than 38 percent and turned the ball over 16 times -- giving up 22 points. And without Davis, they had little answer for the Bulls inside, getting outscored in the paint 66-38. It was Toronto's first loss to Chicago since Feb. 28, 1999, a 16-game streak. "The back-to-back is no excuse," said McCoy's whose 16 points and 11 rebounds were career highs. "That's basketball in the NBA. You have to fight fatigue and can't use being undermanned as excuses." Toronto did manage to hang around until the end of the third quarter, cutting Chicago's lead to 73-71 on Alvin Williams' layup. But the Raptors went cold from there, going scoreless in the fourth until Peterson hit a pair of free throws with 7:50 left. "The guys worked hard, but sometimes it's too hard to get through games like this," Raptors coach Lenny Wilkens said. "We just had no legs tonight." The Bulls, meanwhile, put together a spirited rally. Rose hit a jumper from the top of the key to spark a 7-0 rally, and he turned cheerleader midway through the fourth. Robinson stole the ball from Voshon Lenard and flipped it backward as he was flying out of bounds. Jamal Crawford grabbed it and dished it off to Rose at the other end of the court. Rose coolly drilled a 22-footer to push Chicago's lead to 85-75 with 6:31 left, all but sealing the game. As his teammates jumped off the bench, Rose ran to halfcourt and turned to the crowd, waving his arms as a timeout was called. "Toronto was making a run and I was feeling like we were starting to lose our momentum," Rose said. "I made that shot and I saw (the fans) sitting on the edge of their seats. "I didn't want to keep them there." Game notes
Fans at the United Center weren't seeing things Wednesday, there really was a Jordan running the court in a red jersey. It was Michael Jordan's oldest son, Jeffrey, starting for his eighth-grade team, the Deerfield Young Warriors, as they took on the Leyden Jr. Eagles. The Warriors earned the chance to play at the United Center before a Bulls game as a reward for selling tickets, and the young Jordan looked right at home on dad's old court. Decked out in Air Jordan gear _ naturally _ Jeffrey went 1-for-3 in about three minutes of play. One of Jordan's teammates is Horace Grant's son, Horace Jr. Jordan's mother, Juanita, was in the crowd. ... Chicago hadn't beaten Toronto since . ... The Raptors tied a team record with 20 rebounds in the third quarter. ... The Bulls are 8-4 at home.
